Generating Multicovariate Gaussian Distribution from Uniform¶

${\bf \large \cal Hovhannes \ Grigoryan}\\ {\rm \small New \ York, \ NY}$

Abstract

Using universality of uniform, we obtain standard normal distribution from the uniform distribution. We also show how to generate multicovariate gaussian distribution from standard normal distribution using Cholesky decomposition of covariance matrix. We check our results, and show how to calculate marginal and conditional distributions. The latter is proven to be useful in many instances.

Content

  • Generate Arbitrary Distribution from Uniform: Universality of Uniform

  • Generating Gaussian Distribution from Uniform

  • Checking with Gaussian Mixture Model

  • Marginal Distributions

  • Conditional Distribution

Generate Arbitrary Distribution from Uniform: Universality of Uniform¶

  • Let r.v. $X$ has CDF $F_X(x)$ and r.v. $U \sim Uniform([0,1])$ has CDF $F_U(u) = u$ for $u \in [0,1]$ and $F_U(u) = 0$ elsewhere.

Then, according to the Universality of Uniform, we have:

  • Theorem 1: For r.v. $Y = F_X(X)$, we have $F_Y(u) = F_U(u)$ or $Y \sim Uniform([0,1])$.
  • Proof of T1: $F_Y(u) = P(Y \leq u) = P(F_X(X) \leq u) = P(X \leq F_X^{-1}(u)) = F_X(F_X^{-1}(u)) = u = F_U(u)$.
  • Theorem 2: For r.v. $Z = F_X^{-1}(U)$, we have $F_Z(u) = F_X(u)$ or $Z \sim dist(X)$.
  • Proof of T2: $F_Z(u) = P(Z \leq u) = P(F_X^{-1}(U) \leq u) = P(U \leq F_X(u)) = F_U(F_X(u)) = F_X(u)$.

To generate $X \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu, \sigma)$ from $U \sim Uniform([0,1])$, we need:

  • 1) Inverse CDF for standard normal distribution, AKA quantile function or percent point function (ppf).
  • 2) Using available uniform number generator, generate sample of points $U \sim Uniform([0,1])$.
  • 3) For each $u$ calculate $x$ = ppf($u$), in which case $X \sim \mathcal{N}(0, 1)$.
  • 4) Finally, $\mu + \sigma$ ppf($U$) $\sim \mathcal{N}(\mu, \sigma)$

Generating $x \sim \mathcal{N}(m, K)$ of arbitrary dimension from $u \sim \mathcal{N}(0, I)$¶

  • 1) Compute Cholesky decomposition ("matrix square root") $L$ of positive definite symmetric covariance matrix $K = LL^T$, where $L$ is a lower triangular matrix.
  • 2) Generate $u \sim \mathcal{N}(0, I)$ by multiple separate calls to the scalar Gaussian generator.
  • 3) Compute $x = m + Lu$, which has mean $m$ and covariance $L E[uu^T] L^T = LL^T = K$ (by independence of elements of $u$).
  • 4) It may be necessary to add $\epsilon I$ to $K$ for numerical reasons. This is because the eigenvalues of the matrix $K$ can decay very rapidly and without this stabilization the Cholesky decomposition fails. The effect on the generated samples is to add additional independent noise of variance $\epsilon$. From the context $\epsilon$ can usually be chosen to have inconsequential effects on the samples, while ensuring numerical stability.
In [3]:
def gaussian_sample(Mu, Sigma, n_samples=1000):
    """
      Inputs: Mu        - mean vector of size d (d x 1), np.array
              Sigma     - covariance matrix (d x d), np.array 
              n_samples - number of samples, integer
      Returns: np.array of n_samples vectors of size (d x 1) 
               drawn from multicovariate Gaussian ditribution
    """
    epsilon = 1e-6
    d = Mu.shape[0]
    L = np.linalg.cholesky(Sigma  + epsilon*np.eye(d))
    x = []
    for n in np.arange(n_samples):
        u = np.random.normal(0, 1, d)
        xn = Mu + np.dot(L, u)
        x.append(xn)    
    return np.array(x)

For Cholesky decomposition, we use: np.linalg.cholesky($A$)

$A$ must be Hermitian (symmetric if real-valued) and positive-definite matrix.

This returns $L$ of the Cholesky decomposition, $A = L L^H$

$L$ is lower-triangular and $H$ is the conjugate transpose operator (transpose if $A$ is real-valued).

Generating Gaussian Distribution from Uniform¶

In [7]:
def gaussian_1d(mu, sigma, n_samples=10000):
    from scipy.stats import norm
    u = np.random.uniform(0, 1, n_samples)
    x = norm.ppf(u)  # X = F^(-1)(U)
    # N(mu, sigma) ~ mu + sigma N(0, 1)
    return (mu + sigma*x)
In [10]:
n_samples = 10000

t = np.linspace(-4, 4, n_samples)

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
plt.plot(t, np.exp( - t **2 / 2.0) / np.sqrt(2.0 * np.pi))
h = plt.hist(data, bins=100, range=(-4, 4), density=True)
plt.title("Generating standard normal distribution from uniform using inverse CDF")
plt.show()

Generating a sample from mixed gaussian distribution¶

In [11]:
n_samples = 100000
mu1, mu2 = 3.9, 0.9
sigma1, sigma2 = 1.1, 0.2

x1 = np.concatenate((gaussian_1d(mu1, sigma1, n_samples), gaussian_1d(mu2, sigma2, n_samples)))
x2 = np.concatenate((np.random.normal(mu1, sigma1, n_samples), np.random.normal(mu2, sigma2, n_samples)))
print("gaussian_1d: mean =", x1.mean(), "std =", x1.std())
print("np.random.normal: mean =", x2.mean(), "std =", x2.std())

In [19]:
# x|y ~ N(muXgY, Kxgy) = N( muX + Kxy * Kyy^-1 * (y-muY) , Kxx - Kxy * Kyy^-1 * Kxy^T)

y = 0.9*muY
muXgY = muX + np.dot(Kxy, np.dot(np.linalg.inv(Kyy), (y-muY)))
Kxgy = Kxx - np.dot(Kxy, np.dot(np.linalg.inv(Kyy), Kxy.T))
In [20]:
